It appeared when searching for the specific launch platform.<br>
<br>
I am aware of the ACTUAL high-shots.<br>
<br>
No those were not real space explosions. The highest US explosions were Starfish Prime (a thor launch to 250 miles)<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.dnc.net/users/derf/sfish1.gif"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
This generated a thin, but spectacular glowing fireball and long-term aurora from the atmosphere at that altitude. Altho a vacuum as far as trying to breath it goes, it is more then enough to require space craft to reboost themselves because of the drag.<br>
<br>
The shuttle often has a glow around it from the atmospheric gases:<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://antwrp.gsfc.nasa.gov/apod/image/9802/aurora1_sts39.jpg"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
NASA tiltle of this image is:<br>
&quot;Shuttle Glow and Southern Lights&quot;<br>
<br>
<br>
The other three high altitude bursts were from Argus.<br>
These were boosted by the X-17a rocket<br>
2 were less then 200 miles high.<br>
<br>
Only one went to 460 miles. It would be interesting to see if that shot produced any fireball at all. I do not think any images of the still classified test have been released. I have only seen films of the launches, never the detonations.<br>
<br>
In a serious vacuum, more then a few thousand kilometers up, there would be no fireball (except the tiny - but bright flaring plasma of the vaporising bomb material). The fireball is the result of some material absorbing the x-rays emitted by the blast. No material, no fireball.<br>
<br>
-----------------------------<br>
As defined by the USDOE Office of Science and Technical Information:<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Fireball - A luminous sphere of hot gases formed by the sudden extreme heating of <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> air</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--></b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> by radiation from a nuclear explosion.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->www.osti.gov/html/osti/opennet/document/guidline/pubge.html<br>
----------------------------<br>
<br>
So, bottom line, No Virginia, Nukes in Space DO NOT make Fireballs.<br>
